64. velox, ‘swift’ as being winged, in accordance with the usual representation os Nike or Victoria in works of art. There is probably no reference, as Ritter thinks. to the rapidity with which the battle of Actium was gained. Cp. Sat. 1. 1, 8.

66. utroque pollice: cp. Plin. H. N. xxvi11. 2, 2 5 pollices, cum faveamus, premere eliam proverbio iubemur. The opposite to this is pollicem vertere: cp. Juv. 111. 36 verso pollice volgi, cum libet, occidunt populariter. It is not quite clear what gesture is denoted by the two expressions.
